"## Abstract\nLight field depth estimation is fundamental to 3D vision but remains severely bottlenecked in complex scenes dominated by non-Lambertian reflectance. Conventional epipolar plane image (EPI)-based methods inherently assume global Lambertian properties and utilize limited angular information, leading to inextricable texture-copying artifacts in specular and scattering regions. To address these limitations, a Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model integrated with a multi-scale angular cost volume network (MACVO-Net) was proposed. Physically, a framework inspired by MRI frequency analysis was established to formulate medium and angular masks, explicitly quantifying pixel-level roughness and decoupling reflectance components. Geometrically, an adaptive energy adjustment mechanism was developed using SAM priors and multi-view geometric consistency descriptors (GCD) to differentially modulate regional energy, drastically suppressing specular smoothness pseudo-textures and enhancing feature contrast. Architecturally, the MACVO-Net paradigm replaced traditional EPI structures by explicitly constructing a 4D cost volume from all 81 angular views. It utilized naturally flat cost volume responses in non-Lambertian regions as explicit uncertainty signals to guide neighborhood depth propagation via a multi-scale U-Net. Experimental evaluations demonstrate that the proposed method effectively resolves depth ambiguities, significantly improving the non-Lambertian feature contrast ratio by 495.8% on the Apple dataset, 212.8% on Teddy, and 71.2% on David. This work breaks the fundamental constraints of Lambertian assumptions, offering a physically interpretable and geometrically complete framework for robust light field depth recovery.\n\n**Keywords:** Light field depth estimation, non-Lambertian reflectance, dual-mask physical model, cost volume, geometric consistency"